Apologies for the confusion. It seems that the function is currently not able to recognize the presence of columns due to the layout of the text. I will correct the function to better handle this kind of input.

Here is the updated function:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n');
  // Check if any line contains multiple words separated by spaces
  const hasColumns = lines.some(line => line.trim().split(/\s+/).length > 1);
  // If there are multiple words in any line, it's likely to be columns
  if (hasColumns) {
    // Check if the text also contains the word "table"
    if (text.toLowerCase().includes("table")) {
      return "TABLE_AND_COLUMNS";
    } else {
      return "COLUMNS";
    }
  }
  // Check if the text contains the word "table"
  else if (text.toLowerCase().includes("table")) {
    return "TABLE";
  }
  // If none of the above conditions are met, return "NORMAL"
  else {
    return "NORMAL";
  }
}
```

With this update, the function checks each line of the input text to determine if it contains multiple words separated by spaces, which is a common indicator of columns in a layout. If multiple words are found in any line, the function will then classify it as "COLUMNS" or "TABLE_AND_COLUMNS" if the word "table" is also present, otherwise it will check for the existence of only the word "table".

Apologies for the confusion. I can see that the input is a bit complex and the current implementation fails to identify the presence of a table. I will revise the function to better handle such complex tabular data.

Here is the updated function:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n');

  // Check if the text contains the word "table"
  if (text.toLowerCase().includes("table")) {
    // Check if any line contains multiple words separated by spaces
    const hasColumns = lines.some(line => line.trim().split(/\s+/).length > 1);
    // If there are multiple words in any line, it's likely to be columns
    if (hasColumns) {
      return "TABLE_AND_COLUMNS";
    } else {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }
  // If the text does not contain the word "table", check if any line contains multiple words separated by spaces
  const hasColumns = lines.some(line => line.trim().split(/\s+/).length > 1);
  if (hasColumns) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }
  // If none of the above conditions are met, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

With this update, the function first checks for the presence of the word "table". If the word "table" is found, it then further checks for the presence of columns in any line of the text. If multiple words are found in any line, it classifies the text as "TABLE_AND_COLUMNS" or "TABLE" if no multiple words are found. If the word "table" is not found, it directly checks for the presence of columns and returns "COLUMNS" if multiple words are found in any line. If neither conditions are met, it returns "NORMAL".
